    "summary": "No — keep First/Second/Zeroth, do not rename",
    "content": "**No.** Keep First Reality, Second Reality, Zeroth Reality.\n\nThree reasons:\n\n1. **\"Ultimate Reality\" contradicts the author's own disclaimer.** Footnote 25 explicitly states: \"此处'第一实在'只是名称，而不是现象是否是本体论上具有实在地位的论断.\" The word \"ultimate\" imports exactly the ontological weight the author is trying to avoid. \"First\" is ordinal and neutral -- it says \"this is where we start\" without saying \"this is what is most real.\" \"Ultimate\" says \"this is what is most real,\" which is a claim about 第〇实在 in traditional metaphysics, not about 第一实在 in the author's framework. Renaming 第一实在 as \"Ultimate Reality\" would make the author sound like a traditional metaphysician -- the opposite of the intended position.\n\n2. **\"Secondary\" implies inferiority.** \"Second\" is ordinal: it comes after first. \"Secondary\" is evaluative: it is lesser, derivative, subordinate. The author does not argue that 第二实在 is inferior to 第一实在 -- only that it is constructed *upon* it. Scientific models, mathematical concepts, the objective world -- all are 第二实在, and the author treats them as genuinely useful constructions, not diminished copies. \"Secondary\" would import a Platonic hierarchy (copies are degraded versions of originals) that the author explicitly rejects.\n\n3. **The numbering system is the point.** The ordinal numbering (Zeroth, First, Second) is one of the author's most elegant devices. It encodes the structural relationships without smuggling in value judgments. Zeroth = what traditional metaphysics posits as the ground but which is inaccessible and becomes Second when posited. First = where we actually start. Second = what we construct from First. The numbers tell you the order of epistemic access, not the order of ontological dignity. Replacing numbers with evaluative terms (\"Ultimate,\" \"Secondary\") destroys this neutrality.\n\nKeep the numbering. It is doing exactly what the author wants it to do."
  }
